==English==

{{wikipedia|Articulation}}

===Etymology 1===
{{borrowing|la|articulātus||distinct, articulated, jointed|lang=en}}.

====Pronunciation====
* {{a|UK}} {{enPR|ärtĭ'kyələt}}, {{IPA|/ɑː(ɹ)ˈtɪk.jʊ.lət/|lang=en}}
* {{a|US}} {{enPR|ärtĭ'kyələt}}, {{IPA|/ɑːɹˈtɪk.jə.lət/|lang=en}}
* {{audio|en-us-articulate-adj.ogg|Audio (US)|lang=en}}

====Adjective====
{{en-adj}}

# [[clear]], [[effective]]
# especially, [[speak]]ing in a clear or effective manner
#: {{usex|She’s a bright, '''articulate''' young woman.|lang=en}}
# able to [[bend]] or [[hinge]] at certain points or [[interval]]s
#: {{usex|The robot arm was '''articulate''' in two directions.|lang=en}}
#: {{usex|'''articulate''' animals or plants|lang=en}}
# Expressed in articles or in separate items or particulars.
#: {{rfquotek|Francis Bacon}}
# {{label|en|obsolete|of sound}} Related to [[human]] speech, as distinct from the [[vocalisation]] of [[animal]]s.
#* '''1728''', James Knapton and John Knapton, ''Cyclopaedia, or an Universal Dictionary of Arts and Sciences'', page 146:
#*: Brutes cannot form ''articulate'' Sounds, cannot ''articulate'' the Sounds of the Voice, excepting some few Birds, as the Parrot, Pye, &c. <!--Italics are thus in the source. -->

=====Synonyms=====
* {{sense|good at speaking}} [[eloquent]], [[well-spoken]]

=====Translations=====
{{trans-top|clear, effective}}
* Bulgarian: {{t+|bg|ясен}}, {{t+|bg|отчетлив}}
* Dutch: {{t+|nl|duidelijk}}, {{t+|nl|klaar}}, {{t+|nl|efficiënt}}
* French: {{t+|fr|clair}}
* German: {{t+|de|klar}}, {{t+|de|effektiv}}
{{trans-mid}}
* Greek: {{t+|el|ευκρινής|m|f|sc=Grek}}
* Hungarian: {{t+|hu|érthető}}, {{t+|hu|világos}}
* Italian: {{t+|it|chiaro}}
* Spanish: {{t+|es|claro}}
{{trans-bottom}}

{{trans-top|speaking in a clear or effective manner}}
* Armenian: {{t|hy|հոդաբաշխ|sc=Armn}}
* Bulgarian: {{t+|bg|членоразделен}}
* Dutch: {{t|nl|welbespraakt}}, {{t+|nl|taalvaardig}}
* French: {{t+|fr|éloquent|m}}, {{t+|fr|éloquente|f}}
* German: {{t+|de|redegewandt}}
* Greek: {{t+|el|εύγλωττος|m|sc=Grek}}
{{trans-mid}}
* Hungarian: {{t+|hu|artikulált}}
* Italian: {{t+|it|eloquente}}
* Russian: {{t+|ru|выразительный|tr=vyrazítel’nyj}}, {{t+|ru|членораздельный|tr=členorazdél’nyj}}
* Scottish Gaelic: {{t|gd|siùbhlach}}, {{t|gd|pongail}}
* Spanish: {{t|es|elocuente}}
{{trans-bottom}}

{{trans-top|able to bend or hinge at certain points or intervals}}
* Bulgarian: {{t+|bg|ставен}}, {{t|bg|шарнирен}}
* Catalan: {{t|ca|articulat|m}}
* Dutch: {{t|nl|geleed}}, {{t|nl|gelede}}, {{t|nl|geärticuleerd}}
{{trans-mid}}
* French: {{t+|fr|articulé|m}}
* Greek: {{t+|el|αρθρωτός|m|sc=Grek}}
* Spanish: {{t+|es|articulado|m}}
{{trans-bottom}}

====Noun====
{{en-noun}}

# {{label|en|zoology}} An animal of the [[subkingdom]] [[Articulata]].

===Etymology 2===
From the adjective.

====Pronunciation====
* {{a|UK}} {{enPR|ärtĭ'kyəlāt}}, {{IPA|/ɑː(ɹ)ˈtɪk.jʊ.leɪt/|lang=en}}
* {{a|US}} {{enPR|ärtĭ'kyəlāt}}, {{IPA|/ɑːɹˈtɪk.jə.leɪt/|lang=en}}
* {{audio|en-us-articulate-verb.ogg|Audio (US)|lang=en}}

====Verb====
{{en-verb|articulat}}

# To make clear or effective.
# To speak clearly; to [[enunciate]].
#: ''I wish he’d '''articulate''' his words more clearly.''
# To [[explain]]; to put into words; to make something [[specific]].
#: ''I like this painting, but I can’t '''articulate''' why.''
# To bend or hinge something at intervals, or to allow or build something so that it can bend.
#: ''an '''articulated''' bus''
# {{context|music|lang=en}} to [[attack]] a [[note]], as by [[tonguing]], [[slur]]ring, [[bow]]ing, etc.
#: '''''Articulate''' that passage heavily.''
# {{context|anatomy|lang=en}} to form a joint or connect by joints
#: ''The lower jaw '''articulates''' with the skull at the temporomandibular joint.''
# {{context|obsolete|lang=en}} To treat or make terms.
#: {{rfquotek|Shakespeare}}

