==English==
{{wikipedia|Articulation}}

===Etymology 1===
{{PIE root|en|h₂er}}
{{borrowing|en|la|articulātus||distinct, articulated, jointed}}.

====Pronunciation====
* {{a|UK}} {{enPR|ärtĭ'kyələt}}, {{IPA|/ɑː(ɹ)ˈtɪk.jʊ.lət/|lang=en}}
* {{a|US}} {{enPR|ärtĭ'kyələt}}, {{IPA|/ɑːɹˈtɪk.jə.lət/|lang=en}}
* {{audio|en-us-articulate-adj.ogg|Audio (US)|lang=en}}
[[Category:English 4-syllable words]]

====Adjective====
{{en-adj}}

# [[clear]], [[effective]]
# especially, [[speak]]ing in a clear or effective manner
#: {{ux|en|She’s a bright, '''articulate''' young woman.}}
# able to [[bend]] or [[hinge]] at certain points or [[interval]]s
#: {{ux|en|The robot arm was '''articulate''' in two directions.}}
#: {{ux|en|'''articulate''' animals or plants}}
# Expressed in articles or in separate items or particulars.
#: {{rfquotek|Francis Bacon}}
# {{lb|en|obsolete|of sound}} Related to [[human]] speech, as distinct from the [[vocalisation]] of [[animal]]s.
#* '''1728''', James Knapton and John Knapton, ''Cyclopaedia, or an Universal Dictionary of Arts and Sciences'', page 146:
#*: Brutes cannot form '''''articulate''''' Sounds, cannot ''articulate'' the Sounds of the Voice, excepting some few Birds, as the Parrot, Pye, &c. <!--Italics are thus in the source. -->

=====Synonyms=====
* {{sense|good at speaking}} {{l|en|eloquent}}, {{l|en|well-spoken}}

